    <title>A rough way to measure circles&#39; radius</title>
    <url>/2023/04/02/measure%20radius/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<p>The course, Machine Vision and Measruement, requires us to measure the washers’ size.<br>We got this information:<br>The outer diameter of the washer (the middle and the top one) is 12mm.<br>We need to measure the inside diameter of the other two washers.</p>
<span id="more"></span>
<p><img src="/colorful.jpg" alt="measure radius"></p>
<p>This is my soloution.</p>
<figure class="highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">import cv2 as cv</span><br><span class="line">import numpy as np</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">def detect_circles(image):</span><br><span class="line">    dst = cv.pyrMeanShiftFiltering(image, 10, 100) <span class="comment">#undo noise</span></span><br><span class="line">    cimage = cv.cvtColor(dst, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)</span><br><span class="line">    circles = cv.HoughCircles(cimage, cv.HOUGH_GRADIENT, 1, 150, param1=20, param2=30, minRadius=0, maxRadius=200)</span><br><span class="line">    <span class="string">&#x27;&#x27;</span><span class="string">&#x27;</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    HoughCircles(image, method, dp, minDist, circles=None, param1=None, param2=None, minRadius=None, maxRadius=None)</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    1.image:input image (gray image)</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    2.method:use HoughCircles</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    3.dp:defaults to 1</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    4.minDist = more circles will be thought the same circle if this   value becomes larger</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    5.param1:Canny threshold</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    6.param2:this value should be small if the circle is small. however, it will identify more circles </span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    7.minradius:the smallest radius that can be identified</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    8.maxradius:the largest radius that can be identified</span></span><br><span class="line"><span class="string">    &#x27;</span><span class="string">&#x27;&#x27;</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="built_in">factor</span> = 6/186</span><br><span class="line">    circles = np.uint16(np.around(circles)) <span class="comment">#round number</span></span><br><span class="line">    <span class="keyword">for</span> i <span class="keyword">in</span> circles[0, :]:</span><br><span class="line">        cv.circle(image, (i[0], i[1]), i[2], (0, 0, 255), 2)  <span class="comment">#draw circle</span></span><br><span class="line">        cv.circle(image, (i[0], i[1]), 2, (255, 0, 0), 2)  <span class="comment">#draw the center of circle</span></span><br><span class="line">        r = int(i[2])</span><br><span class="line">        x = int(i[0])</span><br><span class="line">        y = int(i[1])</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="built_in">print</span>(<span class="string">&quot;position of the center：&quot;</span>, (x, y))</span><br><span class="line">        <span class="built_in">print</span>(<span class="string">&quot;radius：&quot;</span>, np.around(r*<span class="built_in">factor</span>))</span><br><span class="line"></span><br><span class="line">src = cv.imread(<span class="string">&quot;image path&quot;</span>)</span><br><span class="line">detect_circles(src)</span><br><span class="line">cv.namedWindow(<span class="string">&quot;image&quot;</span>, 0)</span><br><span class="line">cv.resizeWindow(<span class="string">&#x27;image&#x27;</span>,800,720)</span><br><span class="line">cv.imshow(<span class="string">&quot;image&quot;</span>, src)</span><br><span class="line">cv.waitKey(0)</span><br><span class="line">cv.destroyAllWindows()</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>
<p>Attention: the parameters in HoughCircles should be adjusted as require.</p>
]]></content>
